As is commonly known, the State Blood Reserve administered by the Committee for the Transfusion of the Red Cross was contaminated during the 1980s with an immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and a C-type hepatitis virus.
In view of this drama and the wave of unrest, the Canadian government launched a public investigation in February 1994, which was chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which was intended to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy, and to make recommendations so that such a funeral could no longer be resumed.
While Judge Krever has left the report, some provinces have set up a committee to plan a new system of blood management in Canada.
In Quebec, the Géline's committee was set up.
