"When Hema-Québec began its activities in 1998, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was exciting.
In a systematic effort to increase the safety of blood products and the continued work in this area over the next years, we have regained public confidence," he says and proudly adds that in early 2008 Hema-Québec has already believed 94% of Quebec's population.
However, Dr. Decary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is very fragile."
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998 Hema-Québec has applied the principle of caution.
"At that time we witnessed in Europe the existence of many human cases of crazy cow disease, new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," the woman, who has been leading the company since her founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread blood.
We therefore supported one of the basic recommendations of Krever and Gélineau's report, according to which, in the event that we do not know, and when serious disease is at stake, in this case, Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which marks the degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death, must be taken by an exclusive measure.
So in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that this disease was transmitted to the blood.
So this episode showed us that keeping the principle of caution made sense."
In 1999 a much more accurate HIV detection technique appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that enable the presence of the virus itself directly in donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which tests were used previously were used.
NAT tests have allowed for a short period of noise between the patient's infection and the moment our blood technology can be detected, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this period for less than a week.
We have actually reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing about it and without being able to do so.
This improvement made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusion.
The risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV is one out of 12 million today.
"In other words, it means that before someone gets HIV, he will have to distribute 12 million blood products.
In view of this, Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years before the first case of transmission of HIV through the blood product appears.
I believe that today we can obtain or prescribe a blood transfusion that is necessary for healing," says Hema-Québec's head of management.
"The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen may appear in the system.
Just last year, a Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like a West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by biting the tissue.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that, in addition to safe storage, Hema-Québec must also be counted with sufficient storage.
"They need to grow, because the population will grow old.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecans eligible for donation."
Every healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once in 56 days, that means six times a year.
14% of people with blood supply are not accepted on average because they are, for example, the carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they visited the country where the bathing colds are held, they are excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to supplement the extent to which they are old and are no longer able to donate blood.
But to convince people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so endless that we can only find an hour to be able to donate blood," Francine Décary will get.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart beats, eye bubbles and skin, which is used almost exclusively for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank from the Québec apocalyptic cord.
