Psychology of suffocating: Why are we wasting more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, to overestimate goods.
The neurological and economic basis of this well-known - and apparently irrational - behavior has been able to reveal to researchers in the field of neurology and economy of New York University.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, people don't want to stay in eBay auction competition, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
Research with experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers agreed, the other group participated in field auctions, using the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) examined the active area of the brain of the pilots.
In both games, participants could win money, however in the auction game, the important element of which is to interrupt the other side, began to function intensively when losing a whole located under the brain cortex, called the striatum.
This brain area plays in addition to many other functions in the "self-re rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, it is possible, according to researchers, to explain how to avoid the direct reaction of the street.
In support of their theory, members of the research team from a number of economists carried out a financial cross-check investigation.
Under different conditions, three groups have been competing against one partner.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product concerned and made commitments.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they quit winning, they would get another $15.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also paid these money.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was based on the fact that one was highlighted by the victory and the other loss.
However, members of the "lost" group were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "victory" group, confirming the neurologist's hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
For so far, they have explained the phenomena observed in auctioning the joys of winning and avoiding the risk.
When neurological imaging methods helped us to resolve the dispute between these two theories so that we have now reached the third explanation," observed Andrew Schotter, professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to look for a doctor?
About half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand of them are treated, because the patient often does not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is a summary of the names of liver infections caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, which are signs of inflammation of the liver and the stomach, however, the cause of the disease and the disease they cause differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways depending on the underlying disease: hepatitis type A and E (e.g. food-infected, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other blood and body fluids (sperms, secretion, lungs).
In any case, travellers should be protected by choking against A and B, and no vaccine C virus exists.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after the food is used, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, chest problems, vomiting.
Then, on the skin and the eye whites, there is a yellow, bright chair and a thin urine. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year millions of people around the world die from the more serious type of this disease, from liver cancer and from hepatitis B-induced liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only every tenth infected medicinal product is treated.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to liver surgery or liver cancer.
Most of those infected with their disease don't even know, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells permanently, so the first symptoms are delivered in many cases up to 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, regular testing is very important.
In the three groups, this disease occurs more often than on the average: between people who passed blood transfusions before 1991, between drug users and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C 200 million is estimated.
Since the disease can show a routine laboratory examination, a person should, in case he notices any signs of unknown origin, turn to his practical doctor.
In early detection, the disease is therapeutic, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing such infections and preventing cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was first organized worldwide by organisations representing the disease in 2004.
Its purpose is to note the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of their formation and the importance of early detection of the disease.
